WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:02.400
Hello again!

2
00:00:02.400 --> 00:00:06.120
In this video, we will review some of the finer details about

3
00:00:06.120 --> 00:00:10.720
mortgages to give you a better context on the rest of the case study.

4
00:00:10.720 --> 00:00:15.800
A loan agreement is the borrower's promise to repay the money the lender gave them.

5
00:00:15.800 --> 00:00:23.840
It's essentially a repayment plan that details the terms and conditions on how the borrower will pay back the loan.

6
00:00:23.840 --> 00:00:29.000
In this graph, the loan was made for $100,000, and $20,000

7
00:00:29.000 --> 00:00:33.880
is paid down each year for five years until it is paid in full.

8
00:00:33.880 --> 00:00:37.600
The original amount borrowed is called the "loan amount".

9
00:00:37.600 --> 00:00:44.960
Each period, usually monthly, the borrower will make payments with principal and interest to pay down the loan amount.

10
00:00:44.960 --> 00:00:54.120
Principal is the current amount owed on the loan, which is why it is sometimes called the current balance.

11
00:00:54.120 --> 00:00:59.640
As the borrower makes payments on their loan, the principal balance goes down.

12
00:00:59.640 --> 00:01:05.120
Here, this graph shows the principal balance decreases as payments are made.

13
00:01:05.120 --> 00:01:09.360
This phenomenon is known as "amortization".

14
00:01:09.360 --> 00:01:12.560
The interest rate is the proportion of interest owed on the

15
00:01:12.560 --> 00:01:17.960
principal balance each period, and it is quoted as an annual rate.

16
00:01:17.960 --> 00:01:25.440
However, since most payments are made monthly, we must convert the annual rate into a monthly one.

17
00:01:25.440 --> 00:01:28.800
This is done easily by dividing by 12.

18
00:01:28.800 --> 00:01:36.640
Let's look at an example and calculate the interest for the month on $100,000 with a 5% annual rate.

19
00:01:36.640 --> 00:01:44.880
First, we divide 5% by 12, and we get 0 point 417% as our monthly rate.

20
00:01:44.880 --> 00:01:57.720
Then, we multiply 0 point 417% by the principal balance of $100,000 and get $417 of interest owed for this month.

21
00:01:57.720 --> 00:02:04.240
With amortization, as payments are made and the loan balance decreases, less interest is owed.

22
00:02:04.240 --> 00:02:09.800
Payments usually stay the same, so as the interest portion decreases, the

23
00:02:09.800 --> 00:02:15.520
principal portion increases and the loan is paid down faster toward the end.

24
00:02:15.520 --> 00:02:23.120
Look how the portion of principal and interest changes for this $6,500 payment over 30 years.

25
00:02:23.120 --> 00:02:26.960
Since the principal portion of a payment is different for each period,

26
00:02:26.960 --> 00:02:34.320
Power BI has a formula to find it: PPMT, which is short for principal payment.

27
00:02:34.320 --> 00:02:40.560
The syntax needs a few inputs, like the rate, the period the payment is being amortized,

28
00:02:40.560 --> 00:02:46.120
the total number of periods in the loan, and the current balance which is the present value.

29
00:02:46.120 --> 00:02:51.680
The future value and type are optional and can be omitted or have zeros.

30
00:02:51.680 --> 00:02:55.360
Note that this function produces a negative value.

31
00:02:55.360 --> 00:03:01.040
Also, remember to adjust the rate, just like we practiced in the previous slides.

32
00:03:01.040 --> 00:03:09.360
For example, to find the principal portion of the first payment on a $100,000 loan with a 5% interest rate and

33
00:03:09.360 --> 00:03:12.880
360-month term, we would first plug in

34
00:03:12.880 --> 00:03:17.880
the numbers, adjusting the rate to a monthly figure since the periods are in months.

35
00:03:17.880 --> 00:03:23.400
Once we run this function, it will return negative $120 and 15 cents.

36
00:03:23.400 --> 00:03:30.440
To amortize, we simply subtract the principal amount paid with the payment from the principal balance.

37
00:03:30.440 --> 00:03:36.640
Since the PPMT creates a negative output, we should add so we don't create a double negative.

38
00:03:36.640 --> 00:03:46.640
Following our previous example, the principal balance is reduced to $99,879 and 85 cents after the first payment.

39
00:03:46.640 --> 00:03:53.280
Finally, lenders have qualification criteria to make sure borrowers can afford the loans they take out.

40
00:03:53.280 --> 00:03:57.720
This is highly regulated, especially after the 2008 Global

41
00:03:57.720 --> 00:04:02.600
Financial Crisis that resulted from bad mortgage lending practices.

42
00:04:02.600 --> 00:04:06.040
The first qualification criteria are credit scores.

43
00:04:06.040 --> 00:04:10.080
They are based on a borrower's history of making payments to loans they owe.

44
00:04:10.080 --> 00:04:15.640
Missing payments badly hurt a borrower's score as it shows they may be a risky investment.

45
00:04:15.640 --> 00:04:19.960
In the US, this score ranges from 300 to 850.

46
00:04:19.960 --> 00:04:21.400
Higher is better.

47
00:04:21.400 --> 00:04:27.200
The debt-to-income ratio divides a borrower's monthly debt over their total monthly income.

48
00:04:27.200 --> 00:04:30.680
Generally, lenders like to see this under 50%.

49
00:04:30.680 --> 00:04:39.360
Finally, lenders look at loan-to-value, or LTV, which divides the loan amount by the property value.

50
00:04:39.360 --> 00:04:45.760
Lenders never want to lend more than the property is worth and lower LTVs are seen as less risky.

51
00:04:45.760 --> 00:04:49.400
Alright, let's continue with our case study.

